  "prompt": "Why are newspapers like The Economic Times, Financial Times and others printed on pink paper?",
  "response": "The tradition of using pink-colored paper for financial newspapers actually originated with the Financial Times (FT) in London in 1893. Here are some key points about this unique characteristic:\n\n1. Historical Origins:\n- When the Financial Times was first launched in 1888, it was printed on white paper.\n- In 1893, the newspaper switched to its distinctive salmon-pink color to stand out from other newspapers.\n\n2. Practical Reasons:\n- The pink color made the newspaper easily distinguishable from other publications.\n- It helped readers quickly identify the newspaper in a stack or newsstand.\n\n3. Symbolic Significance:\n- Pink was considered a prestigious and sophisticated color at the time.\n- It symbolized the refined world of finance and business.\n\n4. Continued Tradition:\n- The Financial Times popularized this color, and other financial newspapers like The Economic Times in India adopted similar color schemes.\n- The pink color has become a brand identity for financial newspapers.\n\n5. Modern Context:\n- Today, the pink color is strongly associated with financial and business journalism.\n- It serves as a visual trademark for these publications.\n\nWhile the original reason was partly aesthetic and practical, the tradition has continued as a distinctive branding feature for financial newspapers.",
